-size","content":"`uniku/cuid/v2`"},"282":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-55","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#bundle-size","content":"\\~1015 B"},"283":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-56","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#bundle-size","content":"`uniku/cuid2`"},"284":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-57","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#bundle-size","content":"\\~1.0 KB"},"285":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-58","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#bundle-size","content":"`uniku/errors`"},"286":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-59","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#bundle-size","content":"\\~184 B"},"287":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-60","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#bundle-size","content":"`uniku/generators`"},"288":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-61","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#bundle-size","content":"\\~101 B"},"289":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-62","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#bundle-size","content":"The CUID v2 entry point imports SHA3-512 from `@noble/hashes`, uniku's one runtime dependency; the size above excludes that external dependency's own weight."},"290":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-63","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#reproduce-these-numbers","content":"Run the benchmark and bundle-size tooling from the repository root:"},"291":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-64","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#reproduce-these-numbers","content":"`bench:summary` runs uniku's generators against the equivalent npm package and prints a comparison table. `bundle:summary` builds each entry point and reports its minified, gzipped size."},"292":{"id":"/docs","page_id":"/docs","type":"page","content":"Start here","breadcrumbs":["Docs"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs"},"293":{"id":"/docs-0","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"Ten type-safe ID strategies behind one API, with the fastest implementation of each in our current CI benchmark."},"294":{"id":"/docs-1","page_id":"/docs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs#the-library-contract","content":"The library contract"},"295":{"id":"/docs-2","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"uniku collects ten ID generation strategies behind one consistent, type-safe API: UUID v4/v7, ULID, TypeID, Nanoid, CUID v2, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID. In the current CI benchmark, every generator beats its dedicated npm alternative. Each strategy still has its own entry point, so your application ships only the code it imports."},"296":{"id":"/docs-3","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"Install uniku\" href=\"/docs/getting-started\" description=\"Generate your first ID in one import.\" icon=\"<PackageOpen />\" />"},"297":{"id":"/docs-4","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"Compare ten strategies\" href=\"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id\" description=\"Choose a format by the job it needs to do.\" icon=\"<ScanLine />\" />"},"298":{"id":"/docs-5","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"See the benchmarks\" href=\"/docs/guides/performance\" description=\"Compare every generator with its dedicated npm alternative.\" icon=\"<Gauge />\" />"},"299":{"id":"/docs-6","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"Browse integrations\" href=\"/docs/guides/integrations\" description=\"Start with runnable Hono, Drizzle, and Effect examples.\" icon=\"<Blocks />\" />"},"300":{"id":"/docs-7","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"Use the CLI\" href=\"/docs/cli\" description=\"Generate, inspect, and validate without writing a script.\" icon=\"<Terminal />\" />"},"301":{"id":"/docs-8","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"Migrate to uniku\" href=\"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries\" description=\"Move from a familiar ID package without changing stored identifiers.\" icon=\"<ArrowRightLeft />\" />"},"302":{"id":"/docs-9","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#the-library-contract","content":"Every generator import returns a callable function with precise TypeScript signatures and the helpers that make sense for its format, such as `isValid()`, `toBytes()`, `fromBytes()`, or `timestamp()`. The library is ESM-only, built on web standards, and tested end to end across Node.js, Bun, Deno, browsers, and Cloudflare Workers. The stability contract defines the entry points, validation boundaries, and runtime support policy that take effect with `uniku@1.0.0`."},"303":{"id":"/docs-10","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#the-library-contract","content":"Install @uniku/cli when you need an ID in a terminal, migration, or shell pipeline. It shares the library's formats but has its own release lifecycle."},"304":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"page","content":"Migrate from other libraries","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Migration"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries"},"305":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-0","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","content":"Keep familiar formats while moving to direct, portable imports."},"306":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-1","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"From `uuid`"},"307":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-2","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-nanoid","content":"From `nanoid`"},"308":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-3","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-ulid","content":"From `ulid`"},"309":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-4","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-typeid-js","content":"From `typeid-js`"},"310":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-5","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-paralleldrivecuid2","content":"From `@paralleldrive/cuid2`"},"311":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-6","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-owpzksuid","content":"From `@owpz/ksuid`"},"312":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-7","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-bson","content":"From `bson`"},"313":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-8","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-tsid-ts","content":"From `tsid-ts`"},"314":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-9","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-xid-ts-or-nexid","content":"From `xid-ts` or `nexid`"},"315":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-10","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","content":"Migration is usually an import change first. Keep the stored identifier format stable, then move generation behind the new direct entry point. Every example below shows the value returned by the uniku generator."},"316":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-11","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"uniku only generates UUID v4 and v7. There is no uniku equivalent for v1, v3, v5, or v6; keep the `uuid` package for those, or generate them elsewhere and only use uniku for v4 and v7 values."},"317":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-12","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"The rest of `uuid`'s API maps onto uniku's per-generator methods, scoped to the version you imported:"},"318":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-13","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"`uuid`"},"319":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-14","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"uniku"},"320":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-15","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"`parse(id)`"},"321":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-16","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"`uuidv4.toBytes(id)` / `uuidv7.toBytes(id)`"},"322":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-17","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"`stringify(bytes)`"},"323":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-18","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"`uuidv4.fromBytes(bytes)` / `uuidv7.fromBytes(bytes)`"},"324":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-19","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"`validate(id)`"},"325":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-20","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"`uuidv4.isValid(id)` / `uuidv7.isValid(id)`"},"326":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-21","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"`version(id)`"},"327":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-22","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-uuid","content":"Implied by which `isValid` matches: `uuidv4.isValid` accepts only version 4, `uuidv7.isValid` accepts only version 7."},"328":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-23","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-typeid-js","content":"`typeid-js` returns a TypeID object. uniku returns the canonical string directly."},"329":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-24","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-tsid-ts","content":"`tsid-ts` exposes a TSID object. uniku uses the native `bigint` as TSID's primary value."},"330":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-25","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-tsid-ts","content":"Convert at a string boundary when you need the canonical Base32 form:"},"331":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-26","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-xid-ts-or-nexid","content":"Both libraries implement the rs/xid representation. uniku returns the canonical string directly and does not require asynchronous setup."},"332":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-27","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-xid-ts-or-nexid","content":"Use `xid.toBytes(id)` and `xid.fromBytes(bytes)` when you store the 12-byte value."},"333":{"id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries-28","page_id":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/from-other-libraries#from-xid-ts-or-nexid","content":"Before replacing an existing generator, test the representation you store and expose. UUIDs, ULIDs, ObjectIDs, and XIDs have canonical byte forms; Nanoid and CUID v2 are string-native."},"334":{"id":"/docs/migration/v1","page_id":"/docs/migration/v1","type":"page","content":"Migrate to uniku v1","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Migration"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/v1"},"335":{"id":"/docs/migration/v1-0","page_id":"/docs/migration/v1","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/v1","content":"Prepare for the v1 entry-point contract without changing identifier data."},"336":{"id":"/docs/migration/v1-1","page_id":"/docs/migration/v1","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/v1#move-cuid-v2-to-the-versioned-entry-point","content":"Move CUID v2 to the versioned entry point"},"337":{"id":"/docs/migration/v1-2","page_id":"/docs/migration/v1","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/migration/v1#what-remains-stable","content":"What remains stable"},"338":{"id":"/docs/migration/v1-3","page_id":"/docs/migration/v1","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/v1","content":"uniku v1 keeps its public generator entry points stable and removes one pre-v1 compatibility alias."},"339":{"id":"/docs/migration/v1-4","page_id":"/docs/migration/v1","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/v1#move-cuid-v2-to-the-versioned-entry-point","content":"`uniku/cuid2` is a pre-v1 alias. Use the canonical versioned import before upgrading:"},"340":{"id":"/docs/migration/v1-5","page_id":"/docs/migration/v1","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/v1#move-cuid-v2-to-the-versioned-entry-point","content":"The generator behavior is the same. This is an import migration, not a data migration: existing CUID v2 values remain valid."},"341":{"id":"/docs/migration/v1-6","page_id":"/docs/migration/v1","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/v1#what-remains-stable","content":"Within `1.x`, uniku will not remove or rename documented entry points, exports, options, methods, or constants. Canonical string formats, byte order, timestamp units, and documented error codes are part of the contract."},"342":{"id":"/docs/migration/v1-7","page_id":"/docs/migration/v1","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/migration/v1#what-remains-stable","content":"Read the stability contract for the full release and runtime policy."},"343":{"id":"/docs/reference/cuid-v2","page_id":"/docs/reference/cuid-v2","type":"page","content":"CUID v2","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/cuid-v2"},"344":{"id":"/docs/reference/cuid-v2-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/cuid-v2","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/cuid-v2","content":"Non-sequential, string-native identifiers that resist enumeration."},"345":{"id":"/docs/reference/cuid-v2-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/cuid-v2","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/cuid-v2","content":"CUID v2 is for public values where predictability is the problem. It is string-native, so there is no byte codec to maintain or expose."},"346":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","type":"page","content":"Entry points","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/entry-points"},"347":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"Ten stable generator entry points behind one consistent, type-safe API."},"348":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"Generator references"},"349":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"uniku exposes ten ID generation strategies with a consistent callable-generator API and format-specific typed helpers. The package root is intentionally not exported, so import a generator or metadata module directly:"},"350":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-3","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"Two metadata entry points round out the library:"},"351":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-4","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"Import"},"352":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-5","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"Purpose"},"353":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-6","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"`uniku/errors`"},"354":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-7","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"Typed, machine-readable input, parse, and buffer errors."},"355":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-8","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"`uniku/generators`"},"356":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-9","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"The canonical ordered list of supported generator kinds."},"357":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-10","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points","content":"Every generator exposes its own methods, such as `isValid`, `toBytes`, `fromBytes`, or a format-specific timestamp accessor where applicable."},"358":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-11","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"Read the reference for the strategy you use. The public method sections are generated from the TypeScript signatures and JSDoc in `packages/uniku/src`, so they stay aligned with the library source."},"359":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-12","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"UUID v4\" href=\"/docs/reference/uuid-v4\" description=\"Random, standards-compatible UUIDs.\" />"},"360":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-13","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"UUID v7\" href=\"/docs/reference/uuid-v7\" description=\"Time-ordered UUIDs for primary keys.\" />"},"361":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-14","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"ULID\" href=\"/docs/reference/ulid\" description=\"Sortable, URL-safe identifiers.\" />"},"362":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-15","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"TypeID\" href=\"/docs/reference/typeid\" description=\"UUID v7 values with readable type prefixes.\" />"},"363":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-16","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"CUID v2\" href=\"/docs/reference/cuid-v2\" description=\"Non-sequential identifiers that resist enumeration.\" />"},"364":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-17","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"Nanoid\" href=\"/docs/reference/nanoid\" description=\"Compact URL-safe identifiers.\" />"},"365":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-18","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"KSUID\" href=\"/docs/reference/ksuid\" description=\"High-entropy, time-ordered identifiers.\" />"},"366":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-19","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"ObjectID\" href=\"/docs/reference/objectid\" description=\"MongoDB-compatible identifiers.\" />"},"367":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-20","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"XID\" href=\"/docs/reference/xid\" description=\"Compact identifiers compatible with rs/xid.\" />"},"368":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-21","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"TSID\" href=\"/docs/reference/tsid\" description=\"Time-sorted bigint identifiers.\" />"},"369":{"id":"/docs/reference/entry-points-22","page_id":"/docs/reference/entry-points","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/entry-points#generator-references","content":"<Card title=\"Errors\" href=\"/docs/reference/errors\" description=\"Typed errors and the generator list.\" />"},"370":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","type":"page","content":"Errors","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/errors"},"371":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors","content":"Typed, machine-readable errors for invalid input, malformed strings, and buffer bounds."},"372":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"Error classes"},"373":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/errors#generator-list","content":"Generator list"},"374":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-3","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors","content":"Every generator throws a typed error instead of a generic `Error`. Each one carries a `code` for programmatic handling and a `_tag` for discriminated matching, compatible with Effect's `catchTag`."},"375":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-4","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`uniku/errors` exports four classes:"},"376":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-5","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"Export"},"377":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-6","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`_tag`"},"378":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-7","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"Thrown when"},"379":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-8","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`UniqueIdError`"},"380":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-9","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"(abstract)"},"381":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-10","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"Abstract base class every uniku error extends. Not thrown directly."},"382":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-11","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`InvalidInputError`"},"383":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-12","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`'InvalidInputError'`"},"384":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-13","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"Generator arguments are invalid: bad size, alphabet, length, timestamp, or version."},"385":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-14","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`ParseError`"},"386":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-15","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`'ParseError'`"},"387":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-16","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"An ID string fails to parse or decode: wrong format or characters."},"388":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-17","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`BufferError`"},"389":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-18","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`'BufferError'`"},"390":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-19","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"A byte array or buffer is too short, or an offset is out of bounds."},"391":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-20","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"`InvalidInputError`, `ParseError`, and `BufferError` each carry a `code: string`, a generator-prefixed constant such as `'UUID_RANDOM_BYTES_TOO_SHORT'` or `'TSID_NODE_OUT_OF_RANGE'`, plus the inherited `message: string`."},"392":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-21","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#error-classes","content":"Most generator modules re-export all four classes, so you rarely need to import from `uniku/errors` directly. Nanoid and CUID v2, which have no binary codec, only re-export `InvalidInputError` and `UniqueIdError`."},"393":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-22","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#generator-list","content":"`uniku/generators` exports the canonical, ordered list of ID kinds uniku supports:"},"394":{"id":"/docs/reference/errors-23","page_id":"/docs/reference/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/errors#generator-list","content":"`IdGenerator` is the union type derived from `ID_GENERATORS`. Tools that enumerate or validate generator kinds, such as `@uniku/cli`'s `--type` flag, should derive from this array instead of hand-copying the union."},"395":{"id":"/docs/reference/ksuid","page_id":"/docs/reference/ksuid","type":"page","content":"KSUID","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/ksuid"},"396":{"id":"/docs/reference/ksuid-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/ksuid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/ksuid","content":"Time-ordered identifiers with a 128-bit random payload."},"397":{"id":"/docs/reference/ksuid-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/ksuid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/ksuid","content":"KSUID combines a timestamp with a large random payload. Choose it for high-volume distributed systems that need chronological order and a 27-character URL-safe string."},"398":{"id":"/docs/reference/nanoid","page_id":"/docs/reference/nanoid","type":"page","content":"Nanoid","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/nanoid"},"399":{"id":"/docs/reference/nanoid-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/nanoid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/nanoid","content":"Compact, URL-safe random strings with configurable length and alphabet."},"400":{"id":"/docs/reference/nanoid-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/nanoid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/nanoid","content":"Nanoid is the compact choice for short URLs, invite codes, and session tokens. Its default alphabet is URL-safe; pass a length or options only when the boundary needs a different shape."},"401":{"id":"/docs/reference/nanoid-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/nanoid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/nanoid","content":"`nanoid.isValid()` validates the default alphabet, not values generated with a custom alphabet."},"402":{"id":"/docs/reference/objectid","page_id":"/docs/reference/objectid","type":"page","content":"ObjectID","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/objectid"},"403":{"id":"/docs/reference/objectid-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/objectid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/objectid","content":"MongoDB-compatible 12-byte identifiers."},"404":{"id":"/docs/reference/objectid-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/objectid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/objectid","content":"ObjectID matches MongoDB's native 12-byte representation. Use it when your application stores `_id` values alongside MongoDB clients or needs to preserve that wire format."},"405":{"id":"/docs/reference/tsid","page_id":"/docs/reference/tsid","type":"page","content":"TSID","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/tsid"},"406":{"id":"/docs/reference/tsid-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/tsid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/tsid","content":"Time-sorted 64-bit identifiers for native bigint storage."},"407":{"id":"/docs/reference/tsid-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/tsid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/tsid","content":"TSID returns a `bigint`, not a string. Use it when a database `BIGINT` primary key is the natural representation and you still need time ordering without a central allocator."},"408":{"id":"/docs/reference/typeid","page_id":"/docs/reference/typeid","type":"page","content":"TypeID","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/typeid"},"409":{"id":"/docs/reference/typeid-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/typeid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/typeid","content":"UUID v7 identifiers with a readable, domain-specific prefix."},"410":{"id":"/docs/reference/typeid-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/typeid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/typeid","content":"TypeID wraps a UUID v7 suffix in a lowercase prefix such as `user_` or `order_`. It is useful when a public identifier should reveal the kind of resource it identifies."},"411":{"id":"/docs/reference/ulid","page_id":"/docs/reference/ulid","type":"page","content":"ULID","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/ulid"},"412":{"id":"/docs/reference/ulid-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/ulid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/ulid","content":"Sortable, URL-safe identifiers using Crockford Base32."},"413":{"id":"/docs/reference/ulid-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/ulid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/ulid","content":"ULIDs sort by creation time and stay shorter than a hyphenated UUID. Use them when the value will often appear in URLs, logs, or APIs."},"414":{"id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4","page_id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4","type":"page","content":"UUID v4","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4"},"415":{"id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4","content":"Random, standards-compatible UUIDs with 122 bits of entropy."},"416":{"id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4","content":"UUID v4 is the default when compatibility matters more than sort order. It fits databases and APIs that already understand UUID strings."},"417":{"id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/uuid-v4","content":"Use `toBytes()` when the destination stores UUIDs as 16-byte binary values. Use `isValid()` before accepting an unknown UUID v4 string at an application boundary."},"418":{"id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v7","page_id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v7","type":"page","content":"UUID v7","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/uuid-v7"},"419":{"id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v7-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v7","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/uuid-v7","content":"Time-ordered UUIDs for primary keys, APIs, and event streams."},"420":{"id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v7-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/uuid-v7","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/uuid-v7","content":"UUID v7 keeps the UUID shape while embedding a millisecond timestamp. It is a strong default for database primary keys when you want chronological locality without creating a custom ID column."},"421":{"id":"/docs/reference/xid","page_id":"/docs/reference/xid","type":"page","content":"XID","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/xid"},"422":{"id":"/docs/reference/xid-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/xid","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/xi