 they stay aligned with the library source."],[342,"Read the stability contract for the full release and runtime policy."],[230,"Reproduce these numbers"],[221,"Run it with `pnpm --filter @uniku/examples example:drizzle`."],[224,"Run it with `pnpm --filter @uniku/examples example:effect`."],[218,"Run it with `pnpm --filter @uniku/examples example:hono`."],[290,"Run the benchmark and bundle-size tooling from the repository root:"],[212,"Runnable starting points for Hono, Drizzle ORM v1, and Effect v4."],[169,"See Choosing an ID for the trade-offs, or open a generator reference when you already know which format you need."],[190,"Short URLs and invite codes"],[181,"Situation"],[412,"Sortable, URL-safe identifiers using Crockford Base32."],[292,"Start here"],[125,"Strategy"],[172,"String-native formats do not pretend otherwise. Nanoid and CUID v2 have no canonical byte encoding, so they expose a smaller API."],[347,"Ten stable generator entry points behind one consistent, type-safe API."],[293,"Ten type-safe ID strategies behind one API, with the fastest implementation of each in our current CI benchmark."],[219,"The `binaryUlid` custom type exposes a string to application code while declaring a PostgreSQL `bytea` column. Its Drizzle codec converts ULID strings to `Uint8Array` parameters and selected bytes back to canonical ULID strings."],[356,"The canonical ordered list of supported generator kinds."],[232,"The claim is deliberately scoped to generation speed against the established package for each format. Application performance still depends on where and how IDs are created."],[220,"The column's `$defaultFn` generates a ULID when an insert omits `id`. Both sides of the foreign key remain 16-byte values in PostgreSQL, so the join compares their binary representation while the returned `eventId` is already a string. The example uses an in-memory PGlite database, so it needs no external PostgreSQL server."],[259,"The compatibility benchmark runs each implementation in a fresh process. CI balances both launch orders across four repetitions and reports the per-row median, so warmed runtime state and one noisy run do not decide the comparison."],[207,"The conventional random UUID format."],[289,"The CUID v2 entry point imports SHA3-512 from `@noble/hashes`, uniku's one runtime dependency; the size above excludes that external dependency's own weight."],[424,"The default identity is random and cached for this runtime. Supplying `machineId` or `processId` changes only that field; calls still use the shared counter unless you also supply `counter`. Supply all four fields for deterministic output."],[222,"The example pins Drizzle ORM `1.0.0-rc.4`. Codecs are configured per PostgreSQL type, so this client treats every `bytea` column as a binary ULID. The v1 line is still a release candidate, so check its release notes before changing that version."],[216,"The examples below add Nanoid request IDs to Hono, binary ULIDs to a Drizzle schema, and prefixed TypeIDs to an Effect service. Each is self-contained and runs with the command below it."],[340,"The generator behavior is the same. This is an import migration, not a data migration: existing CUID v2 values remain valid."],[20,"The installer resolves the latest CLI release automatically. Set `UNIKU_INSTALL_DIR` to choose a destination:"],[294,"The library contract"],[317,"The rest of `uuid`'s API maps onto uniku's per-generator methods, scoped to the version you imported:"],[94,"The type is auto-detected unless `--type` is given. For time-ordered IDs (UUID v7, ULID, TypeID, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, TSID), inspect extracts the embedded timestamp. Random-only IDs (UUID v4, CUID v2, Nanoid) report that no decodable metadata is available. Timestamp precision matches each generator: UUID v7, ULID, and TSID are millisecond-precision; KSUID, ObjectID, and XID are second-precision."],[116,"The usual shape"],[225,"This example pins Effect `4.0.0-beta.93`. Effect v4 is still prerelease software, so check its release notes before changing that version."],[171,"This matters when an ID lives in a binary database column, a compact protocol payload, or a cache key. A UUID, for instance, is 16 bytes instead of its 36-character string form. The helpers also make the string boundary explicit: convert when data leaves your application, preserve bytes where the system already handles bytes."],[234,"This snapshot comes from a four-repetition CI run on July 14, 2026. Treat the ratios as directional because shared-runner noise and dependency updates can move them. The rolling baseline tracks results across CI runs for regression detection."],[378,"Thrown when"],[179,"Time order leaks creation time"],[178,"Time ordering is local"],[123,"Time-ordered formats also expose `timestamp()`. Each generator page lists its complete public API, including options, constants, and overloads."],[396,"Time-ordered identifiers with a 128-bit random payload."],[419,"Time-ordered UUIDs for primary keys, APIs, and event streams."],[186,"Time-ordered values improve index locality."],[406,"Time-sorted 64-bit identifiers for native bigint storage."],[13,"tsid"],[165,"TSID"],[203,"TSID"],[245,"TSID"],[405,"TSID"],[407,"TSID returns a `bigint`, not a string. Use it when a database `BIGINT` primary key is the natural representation and you still need time ordering without a central allocator."],[350,"Two metadata entry points round out the library:"],[55,"Type prefix, e.g. `user` for `user_...` (empty by default)"],[371,"Typed, machine-readable errors for invalid input, malformed strings, and buffer bounds."],[354,"Typed, machine-readable input, parse, and buffer errors."],[7,"typeid"],[141,"TypeID"],[188,"TypeID"],[243,"TypeID"],[408,"TypeID"],[410,"TypeID wraps a UUID v7 suffix in a lowercase prefix such as `user_` or `order_`. It is useful when a public identifier should reveal the kind of resource it identifies."],[6,"ulid"],[137,"ULID"],[237,"ULID"],[411,"ULID"],[413,"ULIDs sort by creation time and stay shorter than a hyphenated UUID. Use them when the value will often appear in URLs, logs, or APIs."],[319,"uniku"],[295,"uniku collects ten ID generation strategies behind one consistent, type-safe API: UUID v4/v7, ULID, TypeID, Nanoid, CUID v2, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID. In the current CI benchmark, every generator beats its dedicated npm alternative. Each strategy still has its own entry point, so your application ships only the code it imports."],[349,"uniku exposes ten ID generation strategies with a consistent callable-generator API and format-specific typed helpers. The package root is intentionally not exported, so import a generator or metadata module directly:"],[120,"uniku is ESM-only. Import the exact generator you want rather than a package-root barrel:"],[316,"uniku only generates UUID v4 and v7. There is no uniku equivalent for v1, v3, v5, or v6; keep the `uuid` package for those, or generate them elsewhere and only use uniku for v4 and v7 values."],[338,"uniku v1 keeps its public generator entry points stable and removes one pre-v1 compatibility alias."],[236,"uniku vs npm"],[46,"Unix timestamp in milliseconds, or `now`"],[88,"Unix timestamp in milliseconds, or `now`"],[77,"Unix timestamp in seconds, or `now`"],[83,"Unix timestamp in seconds, or `now`"],[112,"Use `--json` whenever the output feeds another program. The CLI and library publish independently: a library `1.0.0` release does not imply a CLI `1.0.0` release at the same time."],[417,"Use `toBytes()` when the destination stores UUIDs as 16-byte binary values. Use `isValid()` before accepting an unknown UUID v4 string at an application boundary."],[332,"Use `xid.toBytes(id)` and `xid.fromBytes(bytes)` when you store the 12-byte value."],[127,"Usual call"],[5,"uuid"],[129,"UUID v4"],[206,"UUID v4"],[255,"UUID v4"],[414,"UUID v4"],[416,"UUID v4 is the default when compatibility matters more than sort order. It fits databases and APIs that already understand UUID strings."],[133,"UUID v7"],[239,"UUID v7"],[418,"UUID v7"],[409,"UUID v7 identifiers with a readable, domain-specific prefix."],[420,"UUID v7 keeps the UUID shape while embedding a millisecond timestamp. It is a strong default for database primary keys when you want chronological locality without creating a custom ID column."],[185,"UUID v7 or ULID"],[189,"UUID v7 with a readable, domain-specific prefix."],[210,"UUID v7, ULID, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID embed a creation timestamp in the identifier itself. Anyone who can read the ID can decode when the record was created, not just its order relative to other records. That is a feature for index locality and a leak if the ID is public and the creation time is sensitive, for example a document, invoice, or account that should not reveal how old it is. If the identifier is exposed outside your system and creation time must stay private, use UUID v4, CUID v2, or Nanoid instead: none of them encode a timestamp."],[209,"UUID v7, ULID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID carry time information. uniku keeps the state required for monotonic sequencing inside one JavaScript isolate; it does not coordinate clocks or sequences between processes or machines."],[37,"UUID version: `4` or `7` (default: `4`)"],[170,"UUIDs, ULIDs, TypeIDs, KSUIDs, ObjectIDs, XIDs, and TSIDs have a canonical binary representation. Their `toBytes()` and `fromBytes()` helpers let you store and transport that representation without inventing a second codec."],[15,"Validate"],[193,"Values that should resist enumeration"],[337,"What remains stable"],[183,"Why"],[118,"Why byte helpers exist"],[341,"Within `1.x`, uniku will not remove or rename documented entry points, exports, options, methods, or constants. Canonical string formats, byte order, timestamp units, and documented error codes are part of the contract."],[119,"Write into a caller-owned buffer"],[12,"xid"],[161,"XID"],[200,"XID"],[251,"XID"],[421,"XID"],[423,"XID is a 12-byte, lowercase base32hex identifier: a seconds-preci